ODE VI.

In this beautiful ode the poet does not merely describe the pleasures and charms of Spring. His object seems to be to in- culcate a moral lesson. He would show by the rapid succession of the seasons, and the deeay of all things in the vegetable king- dom, that man himself is rapidly passing away3 and that whatever he has to do in this life must be done quickly.
